- Use `spring-boot-starter-data-jpa` in your `pom.xml` or `build.gradle`.
- Ensure JPA provider like Hibernate is included.
- Utilize `@EnableJpaRepositories` to specify repository packages if necessary.
- For dynamic queries, use `CriteriaBuilder`, `CriteriaQuery`, and `Root` from `javax.persistence.criteria`.
- Example of creating a specification:
  ```java
  public Specification<MyEntity> hasName(String name) {
      return new Specification<MyEntity>() {
          @Override
          public Predicate toPredicate(Root<MyEntity> root, CriteriaQuery<?> query, CriteriaBuilder criteriaBuilder) {
              return criteriaBuilder.equal(root.get("name"), name);
          }
      };
  }
  ```
- Apply specifications in repository methods:
  ```java
  List<MyEntity> findByName(String name);
  ```
- For complex queries, combine multiple specifications using `Specification.where()` and `.and()`.
- Ensure your entity classes are correctly mapped with JPA annotations.
- Check the latest Spring Data JPA version on [Maven Central](https://search.maven.org/artifact/org.springframework.data/spring-data-jpa).
- Use IDE features like code completion for `CriteriaBuilder` methods to avoid errors.
